Hi Claudiu!

The problem is that the ID's are too large for javascript to parse from a string into a number - see [`Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Number/MAX_SAFE_INTEGER).

So if you type in the following code into the console, you'll see the loss of precision in the results:

```js
Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER
// result = 9007199254740991 (16-digit number)

parseFloat('1200100000000000004'); // 19 digit number
// result 1200100000000000000 // still a 19-digit number, but precision is lost

// another example
parseFloat('1234567890123456789');
// result 1234567890123456800
```

So, I think the easiest solution is to add a new parser.

The parser doesn't do anything fancy, it just adds a comma every 12 digits (I just picked a nice round number that was less than 16 digits) and sets the parser type to "text". What that does change does is allows the alphanumeric sorting algorithm to "chunk" the value into smaller numbers that can be parsed and compared - [here is a demo](http://jsfiddle.net/856bzzeL/907/):

```js
$(function() {

  $.tablesorter.addParser({
    id: 'hugeNumbers',
    is: function() {
      return false;
    },
    format: function(str) {
      // add commas every 12 digits; Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER is 16 digits long
      // regex modified from: http://stackoverflow.com/a/2901298/145346
      return str.replace(/\B(?=(\d{12})+(?!\d))/g, ",");
    },
    type: 'text'
  });

  $('table').tablesorter({
    theme: 'blue'
  });

});
```

I'll also add this parser to the library so others can use it.

