@tseaver are you talking to me? :)

Applications that don't call ``begin`` now **do** work because we do synchronize the cache, at least for some definition of synchronize.  This isn't changing.

NEO, and in the future ZEO (at least optionally), makes server round trips to make sure any outstanding invalidations (at that time) are received. This isn't technically needed for consistency, except consistency across application instances.  Data are always consistent for a point in time.  This server round trip is expensive, especially for read-only transactions.

