@johnsca I meant that I really do approve of this.  I've had a few use cases where this will come in very, very useful.

I'm also thinking that a 'transient' flag would be useful; i.e. it exists only for the duration of the current hook invocation and then disappears.  Combined with this change, you could do some nice things:

1. Set the transient in the interface.
2. trigger off that flag (to get trigger-flag) in the charm layer to get a 'persistent until I clear it' flag for a handler.
3. when the handler has completed successfully (i.e. made it to the end), the handler clears the trigger-flag.

This would mean that we have fault tolerant 'changed' flags that survive a 'crash', but then 'recover' when juju retries the hook. (I know that this isn't good practice; but it's about trying to be more fault tolerant).

Pseudo code:

```python
# in interface
@hook('some-name-relation-{joined,changed}')
def joined(self):
    ...
    if changed:
         self.set_transient_flag('some-flag')

# in charm layer

flags.register_trigger(when='some-flag', set_flag='myhandler-some-flag')

@when('myhandler-some-flag')
@when('some-relation.joined'')
def do_myhandler():
    ... do something that might crash (as we can never be sure ...)
    flags.remove_flag('myhandler-some-flag')
```

P.S. I've done the 'transient' flag by using a `hookenv.atexit(...)` to drop the flag at the end of hook execution; it only works because `charms.reactive` also sets up an `atexit(...)` handler that flushes the `kv()` store and it runs _last_ because it gets registered before any other atexit(...) hooks :smile:

